    "title": "Geopolitiks Snacks — April 30, 2026",
    "date": "2026-04-30",
    "tags": ["Federal AI policy", "AI Diffusion Rule", "Coal data centers", "H20 export controls", "Critical minerals"],
    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** — April 30, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 🏛️ Washington rewired federal AI policy to move faster and buy American\n\nThe U.S. government has decided bureaucracy was the real frontier model bottleneck. Convenient diagnosis.\n\n- **What changed:** On April 7, 2025, the White House released revised OMB policies M-25-21 and M-25-22 covering federal AI use and procurement.\n- **The policy line:** the administration said agencies should remove barriers to AI adoption, treat Chief AI Officers as adoption advocates, use a single \"high-impact AI\" category for stricter cases, and maximize the use of American AI systems while avoiding vendor lock-in.\n\n*Industrial policy now arrives disguised as procurement guidance.*\n\n**Sources:** [White House releases new policies on federal agency AI use and procurement](https://www.whitehouse.gov/releases/2025/04/white-house-releases-new-policies-on-federal-agency-ai-use-and-procurement/) | [Fact Sheet: Eliminating Barriers for Federal Artificial Intelligence Use and Procurement](https://www.whitehouse.gov/fact-sheets/2025/04/fact-sheet-eliminating-barriers-for-federal-artificial-intelligence-use-and-procurement/?query-11-page=3)\n\n---\n\n## 🌍 Commerce killed the AI Diffusion Rule before it could fully start causing diplomatic paperwork\n\nNothing says strategic clarity like scrapping a rule three days before compliance and promising a stronger one later.\n\n- **The reversal:** On May 12, 2025, Commerce said it had initiated rescission of the Biden-era AI Diffusion Rule, which had been issued on January 15 and was due to take effect on May 15.\n- **The replacement logic:** Commerce argued the rule would have burdened U.S. companies, downgraded dozens of partner countries to second-tier status, and will be replaced by a future framework while chip-related export controls are tightened elsewhere.\n\n*AI diplomacy remains a game of rewriting the licensing map in public.*\n\n**Sources:** [Commerce rescinds AI Diffusion Rule](https://media.bis.gov/sites/default/files/documents/05.07%20Recission%20of%20AI%20Diffusion%20Press%20Release%20%281%29_0.pdf) | [Bureau of Industry and Security](https://www.bis.gov/)\n\n---\n\n## ⚡ The White House wants coal plants to audition for AI datacenter duty\n\nThe datacenter boom has reached the phase where national compute strategy starts sounding like a retrofit pitch for fossil infrastructure.\n\n- **The order:** In an April 8, 2025 executive order on coal, the White House directed Interior, Commerce, and Energy to identify regions where coal-powered infrastructure could support AI datacenters.\n- **The timeline:** those agencies were told to assess the market, legal, and technological feasibility of expanding coal-based infrastructure for AI and high-performance computing, then report back within 60 days.\n\n*When compute demand meets energy politics, every old power plant suddenly gets a second career.*\n\n**Sources:** [Reinvigorating America's Beautiful Clean Coal Industry](https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/2025/04/reinvigorating-americas-beautiful-clean-coal-industry-and-amending-executive-order-14241/?query-11-page=3) | [White House presidential actions](https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/)\n\n---\n\n## 🚫 Nvidia's China chip workaround just ran into another U.S. licensing wall\n\nThe H20 was built to sit just inside the rules. Washington moved the rules again.\n\n- **The restriction:** Reuters reported on April 15, 2025 that the U.S. required export licenses for Nvidia's H20 and AMD's MI308 chips to China, with Commerce saying the policy covered equivalents too.\n- **The bill:** Nvidia said the move would trigger $5.5 billion in charges tied to H20 inventory, purchase commitments, and related reserves after being told on April 9 and again on April 14 that the rule would apply indefinitely.\n\n*Chip controls now mutate faster than the compliant products designed around them.*\n\n**Sources:** [Reuters via WSAU](https://wsau.com/2025/04/15/nvidia-faces-5-5-billion-charge-as-us-restricts-chip-sales-to-china/) | [Reuters via Investing.com](https://www.investing.com/news/stock-market-news/us-issues-export-licensing-requirements-for-nvidia-amd-chips-to-china-3987084)\n\n---\n\n## ⛏️ Critical minerals officially moved from supply-chain headache to national-security file\n\nOnce semiconductors, batteries, magnets, and defense systems all depend on the same bottlenecks, trade policy stops pretending to be niche.\n\n- **The investigation:** On April 15, 2025, the White House ordered a Section 232 investigation into imports of processed critical minerals and derivative products.\n- **What is in scope:** the order explicitly names semiconductor wafers, batteries, motors, microprocessors, radar systems, and advanced optics, while directing Commerce to map import sources, country risks, price distortion, and U.S. processing capacity.\n\n*The minerals story is now just the compute story wearing steel-toe boots.*\n\n**Sources:** [Section 232 critical minerals action](https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/2025/04/ensuring-national-security-and-economic-resilience-through-section-232-actions-on-processed-critical-minerals-and-derivative-products/?query-11-page=3) | [White House presidential actions](https://www.whitehouse.gov/presidential-actions/)\n"
  }
]
